EL NINO, DISEASE PREDICTIONS - USA (LOUISIANA) (02)
***************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
See Also
El Nino, disease predictions - USA (Louisiana) 971020235544
Date: October 27, 1997
From: Richard Nisbett <richard.nisbett@CCLINK.NET.uokhsc.edu>

Nutrients & disease: genotype + environment = phenotype
I found both the recent posting concerning secondary copper deficiency in
cattle by M. Hugh-Jones and the Moderator's (CHC) comments provocative. As
most researchers recognize, the reciprocal interaction of genes,
environment and (for humans at least) culture, is complex. For all
animals, diet is subjected to subtle and dramatic environmental and
ecological perturbations--even in the tropics. Especially for those
interested in multi-disciplinary and organismal approaches to field studies
of infectious disease in nonhuman animals and humans alike, it would seem
to me a productive tack to include data on: physiognomy, trace elements in
soils and dietary items, some known secondary compounds, basic nutritional
analyses of diet, as well as habitat structure (how specific habitat
attributes affect, e.g. vector ecology or foraging behavior under differing
phenological and climatic regimes, etc.). See the reviews by Glander
(1994) and Gibbons (1992) for the role of secondary compounds in fertility
and morbidity in nonhuman primates. Just as studies into interactions of
human genetic polymorphisms and disease patterns have proved enlightening
(e.g. see Clark and Kelly, 1993; Hill et al., 1991; Kelly, 1996; Miller,
1995; Singh et al., 1997), investigations into the specific interactions of
trace minerals and health should offer equally fertile ground.
The effects of numerous dietary deficiencies and excesses for trace
elements and bioactive chemicals have been documented. One potentially
productive inquiry is suggested by a recent report that selenium deficiency
may induce rapid mutation to virulence in coxsackievirus B3 (Beck et al.,
1995). For human animals, ethnographic context, settlement patterns and
nutritional data related to local cultural adaptations (e.g. relationships
between dietary taboos, events such as the New Yam festivals in West
Africa, the "malaria season," dietary cyanate, and sickling) can add
another dimension to one's understanding of disease and "environment."
Examples include the interactions of G6PD, dietary cyanate, selenium and
antisickling (reviewed in Katz, 1987) as well as favism, malaria, G6PD, and
the antimalarial effects of isouramil, an oxidant in fava beans (Katz and
Schall, 1986).
Taking a synecological approach to studies of the community ecology of
disease--especially with regard to diet, nutrition and secondary compounds
in plants--is essential to those investigating relationships between
disease and environment. Likewise, since human diet is a cultural as well
as a biological adaptation, a biocultural approach can be fruitful for
those studying the human ecology of infectious disease

*****
Citations:

Beck, MA et al. (1995). Rapid genomic evolution of a non-virulent
coxsackievirus B3 in selenium-deficient mice results in selection of
identical virulent isolates. Nature Medicine 1(5), May, 1995: 433-436.

Clark, JT and KM Kelly (1993). Human genetics, paleoenvironments, and
malaria: Relationships and implications for the settlement of Oceania.
Amer. Anthrop. 95:613-631.

Gibbons, A (1992). Plants of the apes. Science 255:921.

Glander, KE (1994). Nonhuman primate self-medication with wild plant foods.
In: Eating on the wild side: The pharmacologic, ecologic, and social
implications of using noncultigens, edited by NL Etkin, Tuscon: University
of Arizona Press, pp. 227-239.

Hill, AVS et al (1991). Common West African HLA antigens are associated
with protection from severe malaria. Nature 352:595-600.

Katz, SH (1987). Food and biocultural evolution: A model for the
investigation of modern nutritional problems. In: Nutritional Anthropology,
edited by FE Johnston, NY: Alan R. Liss, pp. 41-63.

Katz, SH and JI Schall (1986). Favism and malaria: A model of nutrition and
biocultural evolution. In: Plants in indigenous medicine and diet:
Biobehavioral approaches, edited by NL Etkin, Bedford Hills (NY):
Redgrave Publishing Co., pp. 211-228.

Kelly, KM (1996). IGHG3 G and the pathogenesis of hyperreactive malarious
splenomegaly. Medical Hypotheses 46:135-139.

Miller, LH (1995). Impact of malaria on genetic polymorphism and genetic
diseases in Africans and African-Americans. In: Infectious diseases in an
age of change: The impact of human ecology and behavior on disease
transmission, edited by B Roizman, Wash DC: National Academy Press, pp.
99-111.

Singh, N et al. (1997). Infectious diseases and immunity: Special reference
to major histocompatibility complex. Emerging Infectious Diseases, Vol
3(1):41-49.

